HARARE - Zimbabwe's longtime President Robert Mugabe turns 93 on Tuesday.Mugabe has been running the country since independence 37-years ago, and is not showing any plans of stepping down soon.He has been criticised in the past for spending millions on birthday celebrations while the country continues to struggle economically. A statue of an icon, a president or founding father of our nation might be worth 2 million dollars. The ruling ZANU-PF party sees no viable alternative candidate to Mugabe for general elections in 2018, state media quoted him as saying this past weekend.READ: Zimbabweans in UK use Mugabe birthday to protest"They want me to stand for elections, they want me to stand for elections everywhere in the party ... The majority of the people feel that there is no replacement, successor who to them is acceptable, as acceptable as I am," he said in comments to state media."The people, you know, would want to judge everyone else on the basis of President Mugabe as the criteria," Mugabe, who is Africa's oldest leader, said.Mugabe has been in power in the southern African country since 1980 and in December his party confirmed him as its candidate for the next presidential election expected in mid-2018, when he will be 94."Of course if I feel that I can't do it any more, I will say so to my party so that they relieve me. But for now I think I can t say so," Mugabe said.READ: Malema to Mugabe: 'Grandpa, you must let go'Mugabe, known for his combative style, said he agreed with US President Donald Trump's "America for America" approach."When it comes to Donald Trump, on the one hand talking of American nationalism, well America for America, America for Americans - on that we agree. Zimbabwe for Zimbabweans," he said.Last week, Mugabe s wife Grace said if her husband dies, he could still run for president as a corpse. "Even a dead President Mugabe can run and win elections" Her first lady ship Grace Mugabe Additional reporting Reuters